"$type":"com.linkedin.voyager.dash.common.image.ImageAttribute"}],"actionTarget":"/in/moheshan","accessibilityText":"View Mohammad Eshan’s profile.","$recipeTypes":["com.linkedin.voyager.dash.deco.common.image.ImageViewModel"],"$type":"com.linkedin.voyager.dash.common.image.ImageViewModel"},"entityUrn":"urn:li:fsd_notificationCard:(SHARED_BY_YOUR_NETWORK,urn:li:uniqueSuffix:(urn:li:none,NmHncV4nTFKhfFmFSfgu-w))","subHeadline":null,"tertiaryImage":null,"kickerIcon":null,"kickerText":null,"headline":{"textDirection":"USER_LOCALE","text":"Mohammad Eshan posted: I was on a call with this dude that runs security at a F1000. Mentioned he was interviewing someone to lead their security awareness program. Their top candidate was super proud of tracking where phishing metrics spike and doubling down on those areas. He was like... that's all commodity scam stuff. The threat actors weren't anywhere near what she was measuring. The bad guys don't give a shit about those metrics. Regulators might, but they're not the ones breaking in. ShinyHunters just breached 300+ companies and now they have CRM records, reporting structures, deal pipelines from hundreds of orgs. And now they're calling employees using that context. Krebs published the actual scripts. It's run like a call center. Caller, Operator, someone coaching live. We're still living in a reality we've created in our heads because of regulators. Why do we treat this like a checkbox problem instead of something that'll actually prevent a breach? Or have regulators just conditioned us to be complacent?","attributesV2":[{"detailDataUnion":{"style":"BOLD"},"length":14,"start":0,"$recipeTypes":["com.linkedin.voyager.dash.deco.common.text.TextAttributeV2"],"$type":"com.linkedin.voyager.dash.common.text.TextAttribute"}],"$recipeTypes":["com.linkedin.voyager.dash.deco.common.text.TextViewModelV2"],"$type":"com.linkedin.voyager.dash.common.text.TextViewModel"},"contentType":null,"trackingId":"VWt7316ARh+PzQSwvNwHuQ==","read":true,